b'@azizansari After all that, I learned a shit ton and put it all down to make a book that is interesting, thoughtful, and hilarious.'
b'We also enlisted some of the best social scientists to help us understand and study all the facets of modern love and romance.'
b'@azizansari We talked to old people, married people, young people, single people, everybody.'
b'@azizansari  The whole thing was more than a year and a half of research, hundreds of interviews all over the world, from Wichita to Tokyo.'
b'To learn about all of this, I teamed up with NYU sociologist Eric Klinenberg and we designed a massive research project.'
b'@azizansari Today, people marry later than ever and spend years of their lives on a quest to find the perfect person, a soulmate.'
b'@azizansari ..and in about 6 months, the new couple would get married and have a kid, all by the time they were twenty-four.'
b'A few decades ago, ppl would find a decent person who lived in their neighborhood. Their families would meet...'
b'Through online dating and beyond, single people now have an infinite number of \xe2\x80\x93 but how do you sort through infinite options?'
b'Online dating is the biggest way people meet their spouses now, more than work, school, and friends COMBINED.'
b'If you are single, you have problems like, "Why did this dude just text me \xe2\x80\x98Hey\xe2\x80\x99 and an emoji of a top hat?'
b'@azizansari If your partner leaves their FB open & you see msgs from someone named Alexia, is it cool to read em? Who the fuck is Alexia?!'
b'If you are in a relationship, do you share your email or phone passwords with your partner? Or keep that shit locked?'
b'@azizansari Love in the modern era is totally unique, strange, and fascinating.'
